@node "Document_0" "Rules for distribution for DailyBackup"

         @{b}DailyBackup V2.4@{ub} is freeware and freely distributable.

         I reject any liability or responsibility for damages to
         your equipment or software or any other consequences from
         the use of this program.

         Use it at your own risk ! :-)

         You can publish the program in pd-series if no money is
         taken for it. But it would be nice, if you could ask
         the @{"author" link "Document_5" 0} before publishing !

         Since version 2.0 the graphical user-interface is based
         upon MUI -MagigUserInterface- by Stefan Stuntz.
         Please read the @{"ReadMe.mui" link "ReadMe.mui/main"} included in this package !

@endnode

@node "Document_1" "What is DailyBackup good for ?"

         @{b}DailyBackup@{ub} ist no common backup-software.

         All other bakup-programs are created to make a huge
         backup on a streamer or anything else.

         @{b}DailyBackup@{ub} is created for those, who are
         dealing with permanently changing or new files.

         You can use @{b}DailyBackup@{ub} to simply say, what
         directories or files you want to be controlled by
         DailyBackup, e.g. your sourcecodes, tables, high-
         scores etc. @{b}DailyBackup@{ub} searches in these directories
         or files for new or changed files and stores them
         in the way you wanted automaticly.

         Of course you can select a packer of your own choice. You
         can do this via a parser. For a full backup simply press
         the button labeled @{"All files" link "Alle Dateien" 0}.

         @{b}DailyBackup@{ub} is a program to create a permanent
         backup easyly.
@endnode

@node "Document_2" "Requirements for DailyBackup"

         Requirements for @{b}DailyBackup@{ub} is OS 2.04,
         a @{"battery-buffered clock" link "Uhr?" 0} and MUI 3.1.

         Tested on following  AMIGA`s: 1200-030-50/7
                                       4000-030-25/6
                                       4000-040-25/10.

         (with OS 3.0, but there should be no problems with
         release 2.04 at all. If you do have problems, write
         to the @{"author" link "Document_5" 0}.
@endnode

@node "Usage" "Usage"

         Usage of @{b}DailyBackup@{ub}:


         DailyBackup 2.32 supports bubble-help.
         That`s why we changed the usage-part of the 
         guide.

         We included a step-by-step-introduction to
         show all beginners how to use this program.


         @{"Crash-course        " link "Crash-Kurs" 0}   Get to know the main-
                                functions & make your 
                                first backup.


         @{"Additional-functions" link "ZusatzFX" 0}   about pattern, packer,
                                parser and much more.


         @{"Tips & Extras       " link "TipsNExtras" 0}   CLI-usage, `real`
                                backups, multiple-prefs and more.
@endnode

@node "Crash-Kurs" "Crash-course"

         @{b}Crash-course@{ub}

         Assuming you didn`t save the preferences before:

    1.   Choose the page `Files`.

    1.1. Add (use the `add`-button ;) one ore more entries
         to the filelist. It can be a file, a path or a 
         device.

         These entries will be scanned at a backup.

    2.   Choose the page `Strings`.

    2.1. Select a destination of your backup.
         It`s usefull to select the name of a disk ("Disk1")
         instead of the device-name ("df0") to avoid 
         confusion.

    3.   Go back to the page `Backup`.

    3.1. Click on `Save date` to determine the time DailyBackup 
         refers to in the next backup. (That means: All files
         that are changed or created after this time are saved 
         in the next backup.)

    3.2. Use `Save prefs` to save all settings.

    3.3. Push `New files` to start backup.
         This function saves all files that are changed or
         created since the last backup.
         
         If you backup for the FIRST time all files will
         be saved. The following function would do the same:

    3.4. Use `All files` to start full backup.

         All files will be saved. The creation-time of the 
         files will be ignored.

         It is possible to make a `real` backup. Please
         refer to @{"Tips & Extras" link "TipsNExtras" 0}.

    3.5. With `Files changed some time ago` you are able to
         backup all files that changed since a selectable time
         ago.

         You can select minutes, hours or days. If you select
         5 days, you would backup all files that changed
         in the last 5 days.

         If you want to compress your files, filter out some 
         files or make a multiple-backup please refer to
         @{"Additional-functions" link "ZusatzFX" 0}.
@endnode

@node "ZusatzFX" "Additional functions"

         @{b}Additional functions@{ub}

         (Notice: Please use the hypertext-buttons in this
          text to get information about the functions)

         If You want to compress your backups, filter some
         files out or make a multiple-backup, You should
         read the follwing :

    1.   Go to the `Strings`-page.

    1.1. Turn on `Activate packer`.

         But that`s not all. You also have to select the
         packer you want to use for the backup.

    1.2. You can do this in the string-gadget below.
         The packer-parameters You`ll find @{"here" link "Packer-Argumente" 0}.

         If you don`t want to make that for yourself, You
         can also click on the @{"PopUp" link "PakGet" 0} to get
         some predefined entries for the packer. Click on
         `LHA into one file` to generate one big archieve
         including all files You backed up. Click on
         `LHA into separate files (no Dirs)` to compress all
         files separately. No directorystructure will be
         generated. A click on `LHA into separate files (Dirs)`
         will do the same with creation of a directory-
         structure (That`s my favourite mode).

    1.3. On the same page You`ll find the `Global pattern`.
         With that stringgadget You can filter some useless
         files like `.info`-files. That pattern work`s on
         all entries of the backup-list.

         The pattern is explained @{"here" link "Filter" 0}.

    1.4. On the same page You can find the Checkmark
         `No compression`. With that pattern you can
         define, what files do not need to be compressed,
         like `#?.lha` or `#?.jpg` files. The files matching
         that pattern will not be compressed, they will only
         be copied.

         For details to define this pattern see @{"here" link "Filter" 0}.


    2.   Now open the `Files`-page.

    2.1. Now let`s come to the local pattern...

         Here You can enter a pattern for every single
         entry in the filelist. For instance `(#?.c|#?.h)`
         to backup only the .c and .h-files of your coding-
         directory.

         For further details look @{"here" link "Filter" 0}.

    2.2. Now it`s time to explain a very usefull stringgadget.
         This gadget is called `Extension` and i really love
         this function ;).

         With that stringgadget You can make a multiple-backup
         of files. With that function You are able to restore
         -for instance- the 8 last versions of Your coded
         sources or whatever You backup! The number of versions
         DailyBackup will create is definable (upto 62) !!!

         A detailed explanation how to use that `extension`
         is given @{"here" link "Extension" 0}.


    3.   Now go to the `Options`-page.

    3.1. With the compression-limit-slider you can determine,
         what files will be compressed and what files will not.
         You only have to select th size of the files. All
         smaller files will not be compressed - they will
         only be copied.

    3.2. The slider for the `Taskpriority` is (i hope so)
         self-explaining.

    3.3. `Highest number is newest copy` will cause, that
         (if You use the multiple-backups) the file with
         the highest number is the newest file.
         Cause this is sometimes very difficult (renaming,
         deleting,...) it could take some more time than
         without that option.

    3.4. `Don`t create name of volume` enales You to
         mirror Your hard-drive.

    3.5. `Show backup-statistics` shows a small statistic
         after every backup.

    3.6. `Detailled backup-status` shows a detailled status
         while the backup is running.


         Before i fall asleep i will go to bed and go on
         working tomorrow...

         ...with @{"Tips & Extras" link "TipsNExtras" 0}!
@endnode

@node "TipsNExtras" "Tips & Extras"

         @{b}Tips & Extras@{ub}

         Now you know how to configure @{b}DailyBackup@{ub} in
         general. You will read about more sophisticated features
         of this program:

       - Use @{"multiple-prefs" link "Group"} for individual settings !

       - It is possible to call @{b}DailyBackup@{ub} from a shell
         with parameters (the main window won`t appear in
         this case). So you can run this program via
         ToolManager or FKey or something like that.

         DailyBackup @{"ALL" link "Alle Dateien" 0}        stores all files and
         DailyBackup @{"NEW" link "neue Dateien" 0}        stores all new/
                                 changed files
         (This would use the «Standard» prefs-file)

       - To call another prefs-file use the @{"multiple-prefs" link "Group"}:

         DailyBackup NEW SourCeS

         As you see it`s case-insensitive

       - Possibly @{b}DailyBackup@{ub} later will support a
         timer-controlled backup. But you can use tools like Cron
         to control @{b}DailyBackup@{ub} and make a backup for
         instance every 24 hours. (probably interesting for sysops,
         coders, and so on...)

       - How mentioned above, it is possible to make a full backup
         with the option @{"All files" link "Alle Dateien" 0}.

       - With the @{"pattern" link "Filter" 0} you can filter files with
         names, that match that pattern.(like `.info`-files)

       - With the @{"Extensions" link "Extension" 0} it is possible to backup
         a file, without overwriting a predefined number of old
         backup`s of this file.

       - Another possibility is to change normal (unpacked) files
         with the chosen @{"Packer" link "Packer-Argumente" 0} into packed files.

         With the option `Don`t create name of volume` you can
         mirror Your harddrive.

       - If You backup a directory AND a file from the same
         directory separatly with an `extension` you should
         filter this single file out to avoid double bakups.

       - Another usage: convertion of uncompressed files into
         compressed ones !


         You got more ideas to use DailyBackup ?  Then please write
         to me ! I enjoy every reply ! Write to @{"this" link "Document_5" 0} smart
         boy ;)
         (Notice: The Guide is NOT witten by the coder...;)
@endnode

